  footnotes: []
english:
  title: A Poem to Present to Ilam
  author: Kang Hee-meng
  language: eng
  text: |-
    Old age brings poverty and sickness—is this not foolishness?
    I do not question Heaven, but eagerly consult the physician.
    My temples startle me, snow-white strands drifting loose,
    And my weathered face grows strange, transforming into chicken skin.
    Having endured much cold and warmth, I am satiated with new flavors,
    And with dear companions near, I have what is truly precious.
    I delight in finding refuge in the empty gate, abandoning worldly affairs—
    Ilam, you alone shall know this heart at last.
  footnotes:
    - Ilam (一菴) refers to a Buddhist hermitage or retreat, likely the residence of the poem's recipient
    - The 'empty gate' (空門) is a Buddhist metaphor for spiritual liberation and renunciation of worldly concerns
